data.name: Label3.Text
data.value: Malaria is an infectious disease caused by a parasite (Plasmodium) which infects red blood cells. Malaria is characterized by cycles of chills, fever, pain and sweating. The Name Mal Aria Means "Bad Air" in italian was first used in English in 1740 by H. Walpole When describing the Disease. The term was shortened to "Malaria" in the 20th century. C. Laveran in 1880 was the first to identify the parasites in the huma blood. In 1889, R. Ross discovered that mosquitoes transmitted malaria. Of the 4 common species that cause malaria the most serious type is the Plasmodium Falciparummalaria. Currently about 2 million deaths per year worldwide are due to plasmodium infections. The Majority occur in children under 5 years of age in Sub Saharan African Countries and about 400 million new cases per year worldwide. It is transmitted to human when an infected Anopheles mosqutio bites a person and injects the Malaria parasite(Sporozoites) into the bloodstream. It eventual get to the liver, mature and infect the Red Blood Cells.
